


{-
    We are going to show you some of the features that the
    Unison Codebase Manager (ucm) provides.
-}

{-
    Not strictly part of the ucm, the Unison languge allows to set a namespace
    for the file you are working in.
-}

namespace ucm


{-
    Instead of relying on comments to describe ucm features, we are leveraging
    Unison `Doc` type.
-}
README : Doc
README = {{
    # Unison Codebase Manager

    ## Graphical User Interface

        First we are going to start a `ui` with the following command

        ```plain
        > ui
        ```

        This will open your preferred browser and shows the project.

        From there you can examine

        * The terms in your project.
        * Search for code.
        * Browse documentation.

    ### Exercises

        1. Find the definition of {egcd}.
        2. What does {egcd} do?

    ## Finding Terms

        Instead of relying on the `ui` to navigate Unison terms, you can also
        `find` them.

        ```plain
        > find egcd
        ```

        You can even find by signature

        {{ Aside {{ Note the colon ( `:` ) used in the find by signature command. }} }}

        ```plain
        > find : Nat -> Nat -> (Nat, Int, Int)
        ```

    ### Exercises

        1. Find the name of the function that converts a {type Nat} to an {type Int}.
        2. How many terms can you find with the name `length`?


    ## Viewing Terms

        Once found you can also `view` the term.

        ```plain
        > view ucm.egcd
        ```

        Or, since the name can unambiguously be determined:

        ```plain
        > view egcd
        ```

        The real super power comes when your system has
        [fzf](https://github.com/junegunn/fzf);

        {{ Blockquote {{ a general-purpose command-line fuzzy finder. }} }}

        ```plain
        > view
        ```

    ### Exercises

        1. view the definition of {Nat.gcd} and {Int.gcd}.
        2. What did you learn?
        3. Does base have your favorite function?

    ## Adding Terms

        The ucm doesn't only allow inspecting the current codebase.
        It also allows to alter it.

        Write the following function, without the `ucm.README` prefix, in a
        scratch file where you started ucm.

        @source{ucm.README.message}

        When you save the file, ucm pick up the changes and offers to update
        the codebase with it.

        Use the command `update` to do so

        ```plain
        > update
        ```

    ### Exercises

        1. Add a definition of your own. For example define a term name of type {type Text}.
        2. What happens when you change a definition, and save the file?

    ## Updating Terms

        When you change an existing definition the same `update` command allows
        you to update the codebase with the definition.
        Later we will see an example that the ucm can determine which code
        likely needs changing.

    ### Exercises

        1. update your {README.message} function by adding an exclamation mark.
        2. update your name to include a adjective.

    ## Dependencies

        If you want to know what dependencies go into a definition of a term,
        you can use the `dependencies` command.

        ```plain
        > dependencies egcd
        ```

    ### Exercises

        1. Find the dependencies of your favourite function.

    ## Dependents

        If on the other hand you would like to know which code depends on a 
        certain term, `dependents` comes to the rescue.

        ```plain
        > dependents egcd
        ```
    ### Exercises

        1. Find the dependents of your favourite function.

    ## Help

        The Unison Codebase Manager is a versatile tool. I you want to know 
        more make sure to use the `help` command.

        ```plain
        > help
        ```

    ### Exercise

        1. How do you get help about a certain topic?
        2. If you want to document the rational of a certain change to the codebase, what could you use?
}}


---

{{
    Calculates the [_modular inverse_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse)
    of a number

    ```
        modular_inverse 3 37 
    ```

    Notice that `25 * 3` equals `75` which and

    ```
        2*37+1
    ```

    so

    ```
        (3*25) % 37
    ```

    hence, the modular multiplicative inverse of `3` modulo `37` is `25`.

    
}}
README.hidden.modular_inverse: Nat -> Nat -> Optional Nat
README.hidden.modular_inverse a modulus =
    (g, s, _) = egcd a modulus
    if g == 1 then
        if s < +0 then
            Some (modulus - (Int.abs s))
        else
            Some (Int.abs s)
    else
        None

